{
  "text": "In addition to the inter-annual and intra-annual trend analyses, an increasing concern regarding climate modes has been aroused. The relationships between precipitation over East Asia and largescale climate patterns, such as the El Niño Southern Oscillation (ENSO), North Atlantic Oscillation (NAO), Pacific Decadal Oscillation (PDO), and Atlantic Multi-decadal Oscillation (AMO), were identified through the influence of atmospheric circulation [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] [CITATION_3] [CITATION_4] [CITATION_5] . However, the underlying dynamics are various for these teleconnections of climate patterns and the seasonal precipitation. For examples, according to Xiao, Zhang and Singh's [CITATION_6] analysis, a negative PDO event can result in an increasing tendency of the spring precipitation over the Southwestern Yangtze River Basin, while the preceding positive ENSO events typically lead to a high intensity of precipitation in spring over the eastern basin. Therefore, these various physic-based climate patterns may aggravate extreme events in different regions and seasons. Understanding the conditions that lead to the extreme and rare precipitation events is of great importance.",
  "correct_citation": {
    "[CITATION_1]": "130025861",
    "[CITATION_2]": "73621681",
